  "prompt": "When is it likely that the proposed extended maternity leave from 12 to 26 weeks will be implemented for private sectors in India?",
  "response": "As of my knowledge cutoff in October 2023, the **Maternity Benefit Act, 1961** governs maternity leave in India. Under this act, **female employees in the private sector are entitled to up to 26 weeks of maternity leave**. This provision has been in place since 2017, expanding the previous entitlement of 12 weeks to provide greater support for working mothers.\n\nIf you're referring to specific proposals or discussions to extend maternity leave beyond the existing 26 weeks, there haven't been any officially announced plans or timelines for such an extension in the private sector as of October 2023. The 26-week maternity leave remains the standard across both public and private sectors for eligible employees.\n\n**Key Points:**\n\n1. **Current Entitlement:** \n   - **26 weeks** of paid maternity leave for women in the private sector.\n   - Applicable to employees who have worked for at least 80 days in the 12 months preceding the expected delivery date.\n\n2. **Additional Provisions:**\n   - **Pre-natal and post-natal care:** The leave can start up to 8 weeks before the expected delivery date.\n   - **Adoption and Surrogacy:** Similar maternity benefits are extended to adoptive mothers and commissioning mothers through surrogacy arrangements.\n\n3. **Recent Developments:**\n   - **Legislative Stability:** The 26-week provision has been stable since its extension in 2017, and there have been no significant changes announced to further extend this duration.\n   - **Corporate Policies:** Some progressive companies may offer additional benefits beyond the statutory requirement, but these are not mandated by law.\n\n4. **Future Prospects:**\n   - **No Official Proposals:** As of late 2023, there haven't been any official proposals or legislative movements to increase the maternity leave duration beyond 26 weeks in the private sector.\n   - **Advocacy and Discussions:** While there is ongoing advocacy for better work-life balance and parental support, any changes would require legislative action, which can be a lengthy process involving multiple stakeholders.\n\n**Conclusion:**\n\nIf there are specific regional or sectoral variations, or if recent local developments have occurred after October 2023, I wouldn't have that information. For the most accurate and up-to-date details, it's advisable to consult the latest government releases or trusted news sources in India.",
